6. You walk into your granny’s kitchen and begin to salivate, as she’s been baking cookies all day. Which cranial nerve is responsible for the sensory arm of this reflex?
Cranial nerve ____#_____, the _____________ nerve(2 answers; separate with one space)
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That’s right! CN I, the olfactory nerve, is responsible for the sense of smell.

You know that all spinal nerves contain voluntary motor fibres, general sensory fibres and sympathetic postganglionic fibres. As you learned in the head and neck block of first year anatomy, cranial nerves vary in their composition; some are purely motor, some purely sensory and some are mixed. Cranial nerves, like spinal nerves never cross the midline; i.e. they innervate their targets ipsilaterally. I’ll recap the cranial nerves here, by grouping them according to function:
Purely special sensory: 
cranial nerve I, the olfactory nerve    , senses odorant molecules in the air, which we perceive as smell; a lesion of this nerve causes anosmia
cranial nerve II, the optic nerve    , senses light energy, perceived as vision; its lesion causes blindness
cranial nerve VIII, the vestibulocochlear nerve, senses: i) balance      , and ii) sound energy which we perceive as hearing     ; lesions can cause imbalance (more in week 41) and hearing loss
Largely voluntary motor:
cranial nerves III, IV, and VI, the oculomotor    , trochlear     and abducens     nerves, control extraocular eye muscles, the voluntary muscles that position the eye in the orbit. The abducens nerve abducts the eye, the trochlear nerve depresses the adducted eye, the oculomotor nerve controls all other eye mvts.
a lesion of these nerves causes the affected eye to be misaligned (strabismus)
cranial nerve III, the oculomotor nerve, also carries parasympathetic fibres destined to control smooth muscle in the eye; e.g. it causes pupillary constriction, and if lesioned, the pupil is large (mydriasis)
cranial nerve XI, the accessory nerve, controls the trapezius (shoulder shrug) and sternocleidomastoid (turning the head)
cranial nerve XII, the hypoglossal nerve     , moves the tongue; a lesion of the hypoglossal nerve paralyzes the ipsilateral tongue; on attempted protrusion of the tongue, the non-paralyzed side dominates, and pushes the tongue toward the weakened side
the function is in the name!
again, the function is in the name!
monitors the vestibular apparatus, which senses our position in, and movement through, space
monitors the cochlea, our sense organ of hearing.
again, the function is in the name; it moves the eye within the orbit.
again, the function is in the name; it controls a muscle that abducts the eye within the orbit.
this name is a little more obscure; I won’t explain its just now.
This name describes the ultimate position of this nerve, inferior to (hypo-) the tongue (glossus)
